{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἀπᾰτ-η</b>, ἡ, <br /> <b>trick, fraud, deceit,</b> νῦν δὲ κακὴν ἀπάτην βουλεύσατο[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.114, compare 4.168\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: in <i>plural</i>, <b>wiles,</b> οὐκ ἄρ᾽ ἔμελλες.. λήξειν ἀπατάων, says Athena to Ulysses, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.294, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.31; σκολιαὶ ἀπάται 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 213. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>guile, treachery,</b> ἄταν ἀπάτᾳ μεταγνούς[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 111, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 230; ἀπάτης δικαίας οὐκ ἀποστατεῖ θεός 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 301, compare “Pers.” 93; ἀ. ἐρώτων 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 617; διαβολὴ καὶ ἀ. 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 6.7, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀ. εὐπρεπής, opposed to βία ἐμφανής, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.86; ἢ βίᾳ ἢ ἀπάτῃ 2.39\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀ. λεχέων <b>a being cheated out of</b> the marriage, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 630\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἄνευ δόλου καὶ ἀπάτης 'without fraud or <b>covin',</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.69; μετὰ σκότους καὶ ἀ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 864c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> Ἀπάτη, personified, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 224, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Merc.Cond.” 42. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>beguiling</b> of time, <b>pastime</b> (not <i>Attic dialect</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Moeris Grammaticus 65), 2nd c.BC: Polybius Hi